@@yThe Northern Pyramid@@N

@@eThe Sand Sovereign built this ascending monument not merely as a tomb but as
a political machine in stone. Its geometry, procession routes, and celestial
alignments make one argument unavoidable: authority over water, trade, death
rites, and timekeeping belongs to the sovereign who can harmonize desert survival
with the heavens.@@N

@@WThe Sand Sovereign claimed descent from the Solar Court's Dawn Liturgists and
hired oasis-trained engineers from the Great Oasis Measuring House. The pyramid's
seven ascending floors encode a simplified imitation of the Great Pyramid's
six-zone progression, stripped to a single purpose: a military-funerary hierarchy
of guardian spirits bound to ascending floors.@@N

@@yAstronomical alignment chambers replicate the gnomon corridors of the Measuring
House at monumental scale. Each calibration passage measures celestial positions
through the same angular methodology the Keepers of Measure pioneered. The
charter road system that once supplied its construction still leaves traces on
the approach: toll marks shifting from water-debt notation to tribute language.@@N

@@dThe seven-guardian binding uses containment mathematics borrowed from the Great
Pyramid's Seal College, repurposed as spirit-binding lattices. This hidden
function was more than security. It served as a backup containment ring,
designed to slow the Black Sun Shard's effects if the Great Pyramid's seals
failed entirely.@@N

@@rDuring the Week of Impossible Dawns, the guardians went haywire, attacking one
another. The Sand Sovereign's spirit on the summit spoke in a voice not its own,
reciting containment formulas in the Seal College's technical language, a language
the Sovereign never learned in life.@@N

@@eThe pyramid still enforces pieces of its doctrine. Ascent means entering a system
that sought to convert administration into metaphysics. Its ruin is dangerous
not only for its guardians, but because the logic still holds.@@N
